<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Zostera</i> <i>marina</i> or <i>Zostera</i> <i>pacifica</i> is dominant and occurs most often in monotypic stands, with no other vascular plants. Occasionally co-occurring with algae including <i>Sargassum</i> <i>muticum</i> and <i>Ulva</i> <i>intestinalis</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 1 m; cover is open to continuous. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Zostera marina </i>or <i>Z. pacifica</i> > 30% relative cover (Leppig and Garwood 2018).</li>
		
		<li><i>Zostera marina </i>or <i>Z. pacifica</i> > 50% relative cover (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Subtidal marine and estuarine habitats. Most commonly occurring on unconsolidated soft-bottomed mudflats in bays, estuaries, and river mouths. Also occurs on sand, silt, and gravel substrates in saline tidally influenced slough channels, and ditches. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (2012 national list) recognize <i>Zostera marina</i> and <i>Z. pacifica</i> as OBL plants. Eel-grass meadows meet the 2020 SWRCB definition of a wetland (SWRCB 2020). </div>
</div>

        
