    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>Widely distributed on marine coasts at higher latitudes across the northern hemisphere, including both coasts of the North Atlantic and North Pacific Oceans, in the Mediterranean and Black Seas, and sporadically in the European Arctic Ocean. See also Sherman and DeBruyckere 2018, NOAA 2020.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa-e, Ah-k). Stands of eel-grass have been documented in the San Francisco Bay, Elkhorn Slough in Monterey Co., and in Morro Bay in San Luis Obispo Co. (Sherman and DeBruyckere 2018).</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Al). Populations have been documented on the margins of Suisun Bay (Sherman and DeBruyckere 2018).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa-b, Ae, Ag-h, Aj-l). Approximately 40% of California’s eel-grass meadows occur in Humboldt Bay, Humboldt County, where it appears secure (CDFW unpublished data; Leppig and Garwood 2018). Humboldt Bay has an eel-grass management plan (Gilkerson and Merkel 2017). The exotic <i>Zostera japonica</i> has been documented in Humboldt Bay and the lower Eel River estuary (Schlosser and Eicher 2007). <i>Z. japonica</i> occurrences were generally at a higher tidal elevation, (between 0.9 to 1.2 MLLW) than <i>Z. marina</i> occurrences, but some occurrences were mixed <i>Z. japonica</i> and <i>Z. marina</i> (Schlosser and Eicher 2007). The Eel River <i>Z. japonica</i> occurrence and most documented occurrences in Humboldt Bay have not persisted and only one occurrence is known to persist (CDFW unpublished monitoring data). Tomales Bay and Drakes Estero in Marin County also have large areas of eel-grass meadows (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bb-d, Bf-h, Bj). The largest documented populations on the southern coast include Santa Cruz Island; Anaheim Bay in Orange Co.; Batiquitos Lagoon, Mission Bay, and San Diego Bay in San Diego Co. (Sherman and DeBruyckere 2018).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Eel-grass meadows provide a complex ecosystem structure that is utilized by hundreds of other marine species for food, hiding, resting, rearing young, and foraging. As such they provide vital nursery habitat for numerous ecologically, recreationally, and commercially important species such as Dungeness crab, Pacific herring, and rockfishes. In addition, eel-grass beds provide several ecological and economic benefits, including oxygenation of waters and sediments, atmospheric carbon sequestration, trapping and cycling of nutrients, sediment stabilization, wave energy attenuation, and Shoreline erosion protection (Duarte 2002).

Eel-grass beds require clear water to capture sunlight and the deeper it grows the clearer and cleaner the water must be, making the species vulnerable to turbidity and sediment inputs (Zimmerman 2006). In California, populations are threatened by stormwater and agricultural runoff, increased nutrient loading and decreased light levels on the seafloor through eutrophication and algal blooms. Eel-grass beds are vulnerable to port development, dredging harbors, oil spills, and off-shore oil and natural gas exploitation.  Eel-grass beds are also vulnerable to sea level rise if sediment sources are not sufficient to maintain bed elevation at appropriate depths, or if shoreline armoring prevents the landward migration of estuarine habitats. Introduced species are a major threat to sea-grass ecosystems worldwide (Williams 2007).

The eel-grass wasting disease caused by a marine slime mold (<I>Labyrinthula zosterae</I>) is a major threat to <I>Zostera marina</I> and has caused significant die offs globally and a 90% decline in the last century along the Atlantic coast of the United States and Europe (Bockelmann et al. 2013). From 2007 to 2013, Morro Bay lost 96% of its eelgrass meadows   eel-grass wasting disease is the suspected culprit. Since the decline, a series of eel-grass reestablishment efforts have been attempted in Morro Bay, many of which have failed or only had limited success.  

California has an eel-grass mitigation policy and implementation guidelines (NOAA 2014).  Mitigation projects attempting to establish eel-grass beds where none exist typically fail. Because eel-grass beds meet the State definition of Wetland, they typically meet the California Coastal Conservancy criteria of also being an Environmentally Sensitive Habitat Area, pursuant to the California Coastal Act.  Eel-grass is also designated by NOAA as “Essential Fish Habitat,” typically requiring mitigation for loss or degradation during the federal permitting process. </div>
</div>

    

    

